Includes the new backup.  Must be > 0"»
  «b::type» 'integer
  «b::group» 'backup)
(put 'kept-new-versions 'safe-local-variable 'integerp)

(«k:defcustom» «v:require-final-newline» nil
  «d:"Whether to add a newline automatically at the end of the file.

A value of t means do this only when the file is about to be saved.
A value of `«c:visit»' means do this right after the file is visited.
A value of `«c:visit-save»' means do it at both of those times.
Any other non-nil value means ask user whether to add a newline, when saving.
A value of nil means don't add newlines.

Certain major modes set this locally to the value obtained
from `«c:mode-require-final-newline»'."»
  «b::safe» #'symbolp
  «b::type» '(choice (const «b::tag» «s:"When visiting"» visit)
		 (const «b::tag» «s:"When saving"» t)
		 (const «b::tag» «s:"When visiting or saving"» visit-save)
		 (const «b::tag» «s:"Don't add newlines"» nil)
		 (other «b::tag» «s:"Ask each time"» ask))
  «b::group» 'editing-basics)

(«k:defcustom» «v:mode-require-final-newline» t
  «d:"Whether to add a newline at end of file, in certain major modes.
Those modes set `«c:require-final-newline»' to this value when you enable them.
They do so because they are often used for files that are supposed
to end in newlines, and the question is how to arrange that.

A value of t means do this only when the file is about to be saved.
A value of `«c:visit»' means do this right after the file is visited.
A value of `«c:visit-save»' means do it at both of those times.
Any other non-nil value means ask user whether to add a newline, when saving.

A value of nil means do not add newlines.  That is a risky choice in this
variable since this value is used for modes for files that ought to have
final newlines.  So if you set this to nil, you must explicitly check and
add a final newline, whenever you save a file that really needs one."»
  «b::type» '(choice (const «b::tag» «s:"When visiting"» visit)
		 (const «b::tag» «s:"When saving"» t)
		 (const «b::tag» «s:"When visiting or saving"» visit-save)
		 (const «b::tag» «s:"Don't add newlines"» nil)
		 (other «b::tag» «s:"Ask each time"» ask))
  «b::group» 'editing-basics
  «b::version» «s:"22.1"»)

(«k:defcustom» «v:auto-save-default» t
  «d:"Non-nil says by default do auto-saving of every file-visiting buffer."»
  «b::type» 'boolean
  «b::group» 'auto-save)

(«k:defcustom» «v:auto-save-file-name-transforms»
  `((«s:"\\`/[«n:^»/]*:«h:\\»«o:(»[«n:^»/]*/«h:\\»«o:)»*«h:\\»«o:(»[«n:^»/]*«h:\\»«o:)»\\'"»
     «m:;; »«x:Don't put "\\2" inside expand-file-name, since it will be
»     «m:;; »«x:transformed to "/2" on DOS/Windows.
»     ,(concat temporary-file-directory «s:"\\2"») t))
  «d:"Transforms to apply to buffer file name before making auto-save file name.
Each transform is a list (REGEXP REPLACEMENT UNIQUIFY):
REGEXP is a regular expression to match against the file name.
If it matches, `«c:replace-match»' is used to replace the
matching part with REPLACEMENT.
If the optional element UNIQUIFY is non-nil, the auto-save file name is
constructed by taking the directory part of the replaced file-name,
concatenated with the buffer file name with all directory separators
changed to `!' to prevent clashes.  This will not work
correctly if your filesystem truncates the resulting name.

All the transforms in the list are tried, in the order they are listed.
When one transform applies, its result is final;
no further transforms are tried.

The default value is set up to put the auto-save file into the
temporary directory (see the variable `«c:temporary-file-directory»') for
editing a remote file.

On MS-DOS filesystems without long names this variable is always
ignored."»
  «b::group» 'auto-save
  «b::type» '(repeat (list (string «b::tag» «s:"Regexp"») (string «b::tag» «s:"Replacement"»)
					   (boolean «b::tag» «s:"Uniquify"»)))
  «b::initialize» 'custom-initialize-delay
  «b::version» «s:"21.1"»)

